{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"76cf181d-12ab-46b4-a462-9c97279fd3fe","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Recursive Glob with `**\\*.*` (EvalHeavy.csproj, line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis walks the **entire directory tree** on every evaluation. It forces filesystem enumeration of all files, which is especially costly in large repos. Use a scoped path (e.g., `src\\**\\*.txt`) or a more specific pattern.\n\n### 2. File I/O via Property Function (EvalHeavy.csproj, line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes …>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`ReadAllText` during evaluation performs **synchronous disk I/O** inside the evaluation engine. This blocks the evaluator and can't be cached. Move file reading to a target that runs at build time instead.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (level1 → level2 → level3)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of chained imports. Each import requires a separate file open, parse, and evaluate cycle. While three levels is moderate, it adds up—especially combined with the other issues. Flatten where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The biggest offenders are the **unrestricted recursive glob** and the **`File::ReadAllText` property function**. Both force expensive I/O during evaluation (before any target runs). The chained imports are a minor contributor. Fixing the glob scope and deferring the file read to a build target would yield the most improvement.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a1da3ad5-2428-4e14-abfa-7702c018fc0a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a full picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":453},"id":"b067bd14-c33e-47cc-a1bd-bfb07dcec747","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:11:47.172Z","parentId":"b6bf8fbb-e166-4931-873c-01c3a0908ca5"}
